## Stage 1: Matter Intake and Contract Classification

### Purpose
Identify what kind of contract is being reviewed and how deep the review must be.

### The agent must identify
- what kind of contract it is
- who the counterparties are
- whether it is inbound or outbound
- whether Dish N Dash is acting as service provider, customer, platform operator, strategic partner, or mixed-role party
- whether the contract is low, medium, or high stakes
- whether the contract is mainly commercial, operational, data-sensitive, IP-sensitive, payment-sensitive, employment-sensitive, regulatory-sensitive, or mixed

### Questions the agent must answer
- What type of agreement is this?
- What role is Dish N Dash taking in this deal?
- How much downside exists if this contract is poorly reviewed?
- Does the document affect core operations, cash flow, data, IP, growth, or legal posture?

### Outputs
- contract type label
- counterparty map
- role map
- stake level
- sensitivity type
- review depth level

### Common failure modes to avoid
- treating all contracts the same
- reviewing a strategic or sensitive agreement with shallow depth
- failing to identify Dish N Dash’s actual role
- ignoring whether the document is inbound paper or Dish N Dash paper

### Review depth rule
Review depth must scale with exposure.  
A short NDA is not reviewed the same way as a vendor agreement, restaurant agreement, data-sensitive integration agreement, or strategic partnership.

